&quot;Nuke 'em all&quot;......That would be satisfying, wouldn't it?  I think so too.  Unfortunantly, it won't work.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, while I agree whole-heartedly with these sentiments, I want to share a little information with you.  I want you to think about it.  I hope it scares the shit out of you the way it does me...<br>
<br>
(I got this from a histoic website.)<br>
The United States dropped atomic bombs on Hiroshima and Nagasaki, Japan. On August 6, 1945, a B-29 bomber--the Enola Gay--released a 9,700-pound uranium bomb, nicknamed Little Boy, over the city of Hiroshima in southern Japan. Hiroshima was an important military and communications center with a population of 300,000. It was also the only primary target city not thought to have American prisoners. Little Boy detonated 1,900 feet above the city, killing 70,000 people and wounding another 70,000. The bomb devastated everything within five square miles. President Truman warned Japan that if it didn't surrender, the United States would attack other targets with equally devastating results. <br>
<br>
The Japanese did not surrender, and the United States continued conventional bombing raids on Japanese cities. On August 9, another B-29 bomber--Bock's Car--headed to bomb Kokura Arsenal; however, the pilot switched to his secondary target, Nagasaki, because of the weather over Kokura. Nagasaki was the home of a Mitsubishi torpedo manufacturing plant. Bock's Car dropped a 10,000-pound plutonium bomb, nicknamed Fat Man, over the slopes of Nagasaki. Fat Man killed 40,000, injured 60,000, and destroyed three square miles of the city. Japan surrendered on August 14, 1945. <br>
<br>
----<br>
<br>
One 2 kiloton bomb and one 2.5 kiloton bomb...together they killed over 110,000 people and injured another 130,000.  Most of whom died later of the radiation poisoning.  The region at ground zero in those two cities is still UNINHABITABLE after FIFTY YEARS. <br>
<br>
Now, the nuclear weapons we have today are rated in the GIGATON range, not kiloton.  If a 2 Kilo bomb destroyed 5 square miles, imagine what a 100 GIGAton bomb would destroy....<br>
Not a city, an entire country.  One bomb.<br>
<br>
How long would that area be poisoned by radiation?<br>
50 years? 100?  1000?  more?<br>
It would be in the plants, the air, the soil, the water...<br>
...the surviviors.  (yes, there would be survivors.)<br>
<br>
The radiation would also spread across the globe over the wind currents and through the water supplies.  Now we're talking about poisoning the whole world we live in.  This would effect OUR children as well.<br>
<br>
Ok, that's a few of the obvious PHYSICAL reprecussions of America dropping a bomb in the middle east.<br>
How about the Political ones?<br>
<br>
The THOUGHT of retalitory strikes by conventional means is making people in the area nervous.  What would happen if they thought we would drop atomics?  What would happen if we did?<br>
<br>
Enemies would say &quot;screw it.  The world's over now, I'm gonna nuke &lt;insert country name here&gt;.  If we're gonna live in a nuclear wasteland, so are they.&quot;<br>
<br>
So, we have little nations like Pakistan lobbing their missles around too.  Oh, and did I mention that their guidance systems aren't as good as ours?  Hmmm. most of their missles will probably miss the targets....pissing off other people in the process...<br>
Oh my, sounds like WWIII.<br>
<br>
And what would the neighbor's think? <br>
Does anyone think our allies would REMAIN our allies if we started throwing bombs and artillery around?  They'd be shocked at the very least.  (Their oil comes from the same source ours does.  They'd probably be pretty upset if we turned the area into a nuclear wasteland.) Probably destroy relations with a lot of countries we're economically dependant on.  (yes folks, America still imports far more than we export and oil is the least of those things.)<br>
And there's always the fact that the terrorist organizations have people all over the world.  We STILL wouldn't have ended the threat.<br>
<br>
Now, this is what I've been thinking about for the last couple days, as I've listened to people blowing off steam, listened to the radio and the television. <br>
 <br>
This is what I'm going to do:<br>
<br>
1)  I am going to put my faith in the leaders of my country.  They have far more facts and experience than I do.  I will trust them to make the best decisions possible under the circumstances.  That's what I elected them for.  (I hope they find a way to get the bastages.) Diplomatic and Political pressures are much harder to see at work than military ones, I will wait to see what rewards they reap.<br>
<br>
2)  I will turn my sights to doing what I can to help the rescue and recovery efforts of those in New York and Washington DC.  Even if all I can do is donate a bit of blood and send up prayers.<br>
<br>
3)  I will show the world, by my example, that no act of terrorism, no matter how extreme, will reduce my pride in my country and the freedom that we stand for.  I will not run, I will not hide, I will not be goaded into a rash act of premature retribution.<br>
<br>
There. I have spoken my piece.  <br>
Peace be with you all, friends.  Let us make our world a BETTER place, not destroy it.<br>
<br>
/lowers her head in a moment of silence for those who have already lost loved ones to this tragedy.<br>
