<br>
The hydrogen bomb still uses a nuclear bomb as it's trigger. It needs it to reach the critical temps necessary for the bomb to explode. The fusion (which is also radioactive, btw) also creates a bigger explosion, spreading the fallout material in a larger pattern. Therefore, there are still the nuclear fallout and the &quot;hot zone&quot; effects that are associated with normal nuclear missiles. In short - we still need to deal with the aftermath and it won't be pretty.<br>
<br>
&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; INCOMING GENERAL RANT NOT AIMED AT ANYONE &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;<br>
<br>
Consider this -<br>
<br>
We are not the only nation that is nuclear capable. Also, there are other weapons of mass destruction, i.e. biological and chemical. To think that we as a nation can retaliate by launching nuclear warheads at a region without consequence is somewhat childish. We could anger our allies and our enemies would see this as the opportunity to strike with impunity. In short, the possibility of WWIII is quite feasible. Am I saying that the perpetrators should go unpunished? No. Rather, I am saying that there has to be a clear headed way of bringing the criminals to justice.<br>
<br>
To those who have suffered personally...my thoughts, prayers, and support go out to you.<br>
<br>
To the rest - we should be united in our time of grief, not just as Americans, but as human beings.<br>
<br>
And no, I am not a hippy protestor &quot;saying no more nukes.&quot; I've signed the dotted line and served my country. Now, I am just a concerned citizen looking at my children and wondering if I had the right to bring them into this crazy world. For their sake, I hope it gets better.<br>
<br>
my 2cp<br>
